Is the defendant in an action in which ‘lis crescit in duplum ² (Tit. 27. 7 inf.) admitted his liability and paid the single damageS‚ and subsequently was able to show that in fact he had not been liable, he could not recover the money as indebitum (loc. cit., Gaius ii. 283), on the ground that his voluntary payment was in effect a compromise, and so by implication a contract. On this principle money paid under asupposed but non-exist- ent judgment was irrecoverable‚ Dig. 10. 2. 36: conversely, if, though there is an actual debt, the debtor pays something different from what he really owes, he can recover, Dig. 12. 6. 32. 3.
